{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604938/1949033101/0421.xml":{"full_text":"Weather Forecast\nMostly cloudy and cool with occasional\nshowers this afternoon and probably to\nnight. Low about 48 tonight. Tomorrow\nfair, cool. (Full report on Page A-2.)\nMidnight, 63 6 a.m. __.52 11 a.m. _--52\n2 a.m. -_-59 8 a.m. 51 Noon_52\n4 a.m. .--56 10 a.m. _--52 1 p.m. 50\nLate New York Markets, Page A-31.\nGuide for Readers]\npast Past\nAfter Dark_A-25 Lost and Found, A-3\nAmusements .-.B-8 Obituary -A-26\nComics .C-10-11 Radio -C-ll\nEditorial_A-18 Society. Clubs...B-3\nEd'rial Articles, A-19 Sports-C-l-3\nFinance_A-31 Woman's Page.B-18\nAn Associated Press Newspaper\n97th Year. No. 89. Phone ST. 5000\nS WASHINGTON, H. C., THURSDAY, MARCH 31, 1949\u2014SIXTY-FOUR PAGUB.\nCity Home Delivery, Daily and Sunday, $1.20 a Month. When 5\nSundays, $1.30. Night Pinal Edition. $1.30 and $1.40 per Month vuxi\nDow Chemical\nPresident Dies\nin Plane Crash\nWife and Two Others\nAlso Killed; One Man\nIs Taken to Hospital\nBy the Associated Press\nLONDON, Ontario, Mar. 31.\u2014\nDr. Willard H. Dow, 52, president\nof the Dow Chemical Co. in Mid\nland, Mich., and three others were\nkilled when their plane crashed\nand burned near here today.\nAmong the victims was Mr.\nDow\u2019s wife, Martha.\nPolice identified the other vic\ntims as the pilot, A. J. Bowie, and\nMrs. Calvin Campbell, 45, of\nMidland.\nMrs. Campbell\u2019s husband, 46,\nwas taken to St. Joseph's Hospital.\nPolice said the private aircraft\nstruck the ground 1 mile from\nthe city airport at 10:15 a.m. It\nwas near the village of Fran\nshawe.\nAirport officials believed that\nicing conditions might have\ncaused the crash.\nThe Dows are parents of two\nchildren.\nOfficials of Massachusetts Insti\nDR. WILLARD H. DOW.\n\u2014Wide World Photo.\ntute of Technology at Cambridge,\nsaid Dr. Dow' was traveling there\nto participate as a distinguished\nguest in that institution's mid\ncentury convocation which is to\nbe addressed tonight by former\nPrime Minister Churchill of Great\nBritain.\nPolice said the aircraft struck\na farmer's field and burst into'\nflames.\nThe Dow Cheibical Co. is one\nof the world\u2019s largest manufac\nturers of chemical products.\nWillard Henry Dow, chairman of\nthe board, president and general\nmanager of the Dow Chemical Co.,\nwas bom January 4, 1897. at Mid\nland. Mich.\nHe received his early education\nat Midland High School, later\nattending the University of Mich\nigan. receiving his bachelor of\nscience degree in chemical engi\nneering in 1919. In that same\nyear he began his career with the\ncompany as chemical engineer,\nworking in various capacities\nthroughout the extensive plants.\nIn 1922 he was made a director\nof the company, and assistant\ngeneral- manager in 1926. Upon\nhis father\u2019s death in 1930, he took\nover th\u00ab duties of president and\ngeneral manager, and in 1941 be\ncame chairman of the board.\nHe was also president of Ethyl\nDow Chemical Co.. Midland Am\nmonia Co., and Dow Chemical of\nCanada, Ltd. _\nWest Virginia Bridge\nCollapses, Killing 4\nBy tht Associated Press\nHINTON, W. Va., Mar. 31\nFour men were killed when the\nnew Bluestone River bridge being\nbuilt near here collapsed in a high\nwind today.\nC. C. Stevefeld, superintendent\nof the project, identified two of\nthe casualties as Paul Sanders and\nJohn Albert of Radford, Va.\nThe 'men fell 200 feet into the\nriver. Three died in the water, a\nfourth as efforts were being made\nto revive him with a pulmotor.\nFive others were injured and\nbrought to a hospital here.\nThe highway bridge is being\nconstructed at the side of the\nBluestone flood-control dam, about\n4 miles from Hinton.\nFrank Young, 32, of Radford\nsaid he was the only one of the\nmen on the bridge to get out. He\n,said there was no warning of the\nCollapse.\n\u201cI was lucky,\u201d he said. \u2018\u2018I had\na hard time getting back to the\ntop. It was a pretty bad feeling.\u201d\nAt a hospital here, three of the\nother injured were identified as\nOak Fahzer, John Carter and\nVirgil Thompson, all of Radford.\nPersons at the scene said a 260\nfoot bridge span being put across\nthe river had been completed to\nwithin about 60 feet of the center\npier. The 200-foot completed sec\ntion collapsed into the river.\nLamb Prices Set Record\nCHICAGO, Mar. 31 (IP).\u2014Fed\nlambs eked out another record\nhigh price today at $32.25, up 25\ncents, a hundred pounds from the\nprevious peak set yesterday. The\nhew high on winter marketed\nlambs was within a quarter of the\nall-time record here last made in\nJuly for spring lambs.\nI\nGrand Jury Hears Sam Beard\nIn Two Brief Appearances\nEx-Kingpin in District\nGambling Refuses to\nDiscuss Testimony\nSam Beard, one-time kingpin of\nWashington gambling, made two\nbrief appearances today before the\nspecial grand jury investigating\nthe gambling racket here.\nOn his first visit, he stayed 10\nminutes. When he returned an\nhour later, he stayed in the jury\nroom 2 minutes. Then the special\ngrand jury went to lunch.\nThe avowed gambler refused to\ndiscuss his testimony.\nBeard was the first witness\nsummoned as the special grand\njury resumed its inquiry into the\nlinks between Maryland sources\nof race track information and\nWashington bookies.\nExcept for a moment when he\ngrinned fleetingly at photogra\nphers, Beard maintained a poker\nface and refused to talk to re\nporters. He even refused to ad\nmit; he was Sam Beard.\nArriving well in advance of the\nsession, the paunchy witness set\ntled his girth in a chair outside\nthe United States Attorney\u2019s office\nand thumbed through a news\nmagazine.\nUnited States Attorney George\nMorris Fay and Assistant United\nStates Attorney John W. Fihelly\nwalked past him without looking\nhis way. A few minutes later, a\ndeputy marshal was sent for him.\nAfter his first brief appearance\nreporters pressed him fruitlessly\nfor comment. When he reached the\ndoor and saw photographers lined\nj (Continued on Page A-6, Col. 2.t\nTruman Is Confident\nSenate Will Ratify\nAtlantic Alliance\nAcheson to Confer With\nBevin and Stikker Today\nOn Strengthening Unity\nPresident Truman declared to\nday that he is confident the At\nlantic Pact will be ratified by the\nSenate. He said the defense alli\nance is absolutely necessary.\nThe President took this position\nat a news conference when he\nwas told that Senator Taft, Re\npublican. of Ohio has questioned\nthe advisability of going into the\npact. Mr. Truman wid he thought\nfthe majority of the Senators would\ngo along with the pact.\nMr. Truman restated his stand\nas Secretary of State Acheson ar\nranged to meet today with British\nForeign Secretary Bevin and\nNetherlands Foreign Minister\nStikker in a new series of top\nlevel informal talks designed to\nsolidify the unity of the North\nAtlantic treaty powers.\nBevin Appointment at 2:30.\nMr. Bevin was scheduled to see\nMr. Acheson at 2:30 p.m. Mr.\nStikker arranged to confer with\nthe Secretary at 4:30 p.m.\nMr. Bevin and Mr. Stikker ar\nrived here yesterday to join Mr.\nAcheson and the Foreign Min\nisters of 9 other nations in\nsigning next Monday the historic\npact linking North America and\nWestern Europe in a defense\nalliance against aggression from\nRussia or any other source.\nHeads of the foreign offices of\nFrance, Canada, Belgium, the\nNetherlands, Luxembourg, Norway,\nItaly, Denmark, Portugal and Ice\nland were due here at various\n.times today and tomorrow to\ncomplete the lineup of 12 signers\nof the treaty.\nTalks to Go Beyond Pact.\nIn informal conferences before\nand after the pact signing, Mr.\nAcheson expects to discuss with\nthe visiting officials all questions\nof mutual interest they want to\nbring up. These talks will go\nbeyond the North Atlantic pact\nitself to cover the whole problem\nof reinforcing unity of the West\nern powers in building peace.\nMr. Acheson said at a news con\nference yesterday that one of the\nmost important questions to be\ndiscussed, especially between him\nself, Mr. Bevin and French For\neign Minister Schuman, concerns\nWestern Germany. He plans to\nsee Mr. Schuman tomorrow. The\nthree will seek to advance settle\nment of differences about creation\nof a single German government\nover the American, British and\nFrench occupation zones.\nThe talks also may touch on\nsuch questions as security of the\nMiddle East, especially such coun\ntries as Greece, Turkey and Iran;\nhow to block the spread of Com\n(See ATLANTIC PACT. Pg. A-5.)\nSAM BEARD.\nLeaving District Court after\ntestifying today before a spe\ncial grand fury.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nTruman Urges Senate\nTo Defeat Slash in\nForeign Aid Funds\nFull Amount Is Needed,\nHe Tells Press Parley;\nMay Vote on Cut Today\nPresident Truman insisted to\nday that Congress provide the full\n$5,580,000,000 sought by the ad\nministration for the European\nRecovery Program.\nThe President declared at his\nnews conference that this amount\nis necessary to run the program.\nHe said it ha<l been worked out\nvery carefully.\nThe foreign aid program, he said\nbluntly, should not be cut at all.\nThe President made his observa\ni tion when he was questioned about\nefforts of Senators Taft, Repub\nlican, of Ohio and Russell, Demo\ncrat, of Georgia to cut the amount\nsought by the idministration.\nI Administration forces in Con\ngress claimed they had enough\nvotes to \u201cbreak the back\u201d of a\nRepublican-led drive for an ECA\ncut.\n1 Both Sides Voice Confidence.\nMajority Leader Lucas and\nChairman Connally of the Senate\nForeign Relations Committee be\nS lieve they have the votes to beat it,\non the basis of an informal poll.\nBut Senator Taft, chairman\nof the Senate Republican Policy\nCommittee, says the amend\nment has \u201ca pretty good chance.\u201d\nBoth parties are split on the issue1,\nand in such a situation the scales\ncould be tipped either way.\n\u201cWe will beat it,\u201d said Senator\nLucas, referring to the 10 per cent\n!cut, \"and when we do that will\nbreak the back of the move to\nreduce the total.\u201d\nOther Amendments Pending.\nI Waiting to be taken up later\nare other amendments including\nthe following:\nBy Minority Leader Wherry to\nreduce the authorization from $5,\n580,000,000 to $3,638,000,000 and\nlimit it to 12 instead of 15 months.\nBy Senator Capehart, Repub\nlican, of Indiana, to cut the total\nto $3,000,000,000.\nBoth sides agree that the Taft\ni Russell motion will be the real\ntest. If that fails, the more\ndrastic reductions will have no\nchance.\nFinal Action Unlikely Today\nThe Senate probably will not\npass the bill before tomorrow,\neven if it settles on the amount\ntoday. There are other amend\nments affecting the scope of the\nMarshall plan, some of which may\nlead to further debate.\nSenator Brewster, Republican,\nof Maine has an amendment that\nwould bar further Marshal plan\naid to the Netherlands unless it\ncomplies with a U. N. cease-fire\norder in Indonesia. Some Sena\ntors say this amendment may give\n(See FOREIGN AID, Page A-3t\nJoe Fox for Commissioner?\nCouldn't Do Worse, He Admits\nPresident Truman told his news\nconference today that Joseph A.\nFox, White House reporter for\nThe Star, had been mentioned\nfor the District Commissioner\nship\u2014but he got slightly con\nfused on the reputed sponsors.\nThe President had just been\ngiving the \u201creal estate lobby\u201d a\ngoing over when William H. Law\nrence, a reporter for the New\nYork Times, wanted to know\nabout \u201creports\u201d that Mr. Fox was\nbeing considered.\nThe President, smiling, said\nthat Mr. Fox's name had been\noffered by what he described as\nsome very eminent real estate\nmen.\nWhen a roar went up from the\nconference, the President, joining\nin, said hastily that he was still\nthinking about the real estate men\nbut what he actually meant was\nnewspapermen.\nThe victim protested that he\npractically had been libeled. The\nPresident agreed.\nAsked for comment later on his\nbeing mentioned for the Commis\nsioner post, Mr. Fox, who is from\nthe President\u2019s home State of Mis\nsouri, asserted:\n\"They couldn\u2019t do worse.\u201d\nTrumanStillCalls\nFor Tax Boost,\nStandby Curbs\nSays Nation Faces\nDeficit in Disputing\nGeorge's Views\nMERCHANTS\u2019 CAUTIOUS Buy\ning Chief Cause of Slump in\nBusiness Loans. Page A-31.\nBy Joseph A. Fox\nPresident Truman said today he\nstill wants a $4,000,000,000 tax\nincrease and his anti-inflation\nprogram, including standby price\ncontrols, to keep the Nation\u2019s\neconomy steady.\nMr. Truman told a news con\nference that the deficit facing the\nNation at the end of the current\nfiscal year offers a far more seri\nous threat to a stable economy\nthan would a tax increase.\nHe made the statement in dis\nagreeing with views expressed by\nSenator George, Democrat, of\nGeorgia that the tax increase\nrequested by the administration\nwould be a sure way to send the\ncountry into a depression. The\nPresident said flatly he thought\nSenator George was wrong.\nMr. Truman has estimated a\n$600,000,000 to $700,000,000 deficit\non June 30.\nEmphatic on Controls.\nMr. Truman also was emphatic\nin declaring he is sticking by his\nrequest for standby price and wage\ncontrols. He emphasized that he\nthought they were as necessary\nnow as they ever have been, de\nspite evidence that the inflationary\nthreat is disappearing.\nThe fact that he had asked for\nthe curbs, the President tpjd a\nquestioner, was a big factor in\nwarding off inflation.\nMr. Truman declared he knew\nnothing about the shelving of his\nrequest for standby controls and\nadded that he thought he would\nhave been informed if such a step\nhad been taken. Key Democratic\nSenators were reported today as\nagreeing that the current read\njustment in the Nation's economy\nprobably had removed any need\nfor the controls asked by Mr.\nTruman.\nThe President, to nis news con\nference discussion of economic\nconditions, said he would ask for\na year\u2019s extension of curbs on\ninstallment buying.\nHe also said that Dr. Edwin G.\nNourse is not resigning as chair\nman of the President\u2019s Council of\nEconomic Advisers, as Dr. Nourse\nhimself said yesterday. There\nhave been reports that Dr. Nourse\nwas resigning because of differ\nences with the other two members\nof the council over the way the\nadministration is handling the\neconomic situation.\nOne of the Democratic leaders,\ncommenting on whether the Pres\nident now requires standby price\nand wage controls was Senator\nO'Mahoney of Wyoming, who said:\n\u201cThere can be no doubt that\nrecent price decreases have re\nduced demands for controls.\u201d\nHearings May Be Delayed.\nAs chairman of the Joint Sen\nate-House Economic Committee.\nSenator O\u2019Mahoney previously\naad urged the standby authority\nfor the President to invoke selec\ntive price and even wage controls\nto meet dangers of inflation.\nSenate Majority Leader Lucas\nraid the presidential controls bill\nis not on a list of measures now\nbeing pushed.\ni And Chairman Maybank of the\nSenate Banking Committee said\nany hearings on controls probably\nwill be delayed for some time.\nChairman McClellan of the Sen\nate Expenditures Cemmittee said\nin a separate interview:\ni \u201cFrankly I think the danger of\ninflation is passed.\u201d\nSnyder Statement Supported.\nAll four Democrats agreed with\nSecretary of the Treasury Snyder\u2019s\npress conference estimate yester\nday that the Nation is \u201cunder\ngoing healthy readjustment\u201d and\nthe business outlook is for con\ntinued prosperity.\nMr. Snyder said the Govern\nment could not lower its tax rev\nenue total. That was an apparent\nrebuff for congressional sugges\ntions of new tax reductions. But\nat the same time the Secretary\nmade no mention of President\nTruman's earlier demands for\n$4,000,000,000 of new taxes.\nDr. Nourse failed to plug for\ngovernment controls yesterday\nafter a talk with the President.\nDr. Nourse said inflationary\ndangers still are \u201cpossible.\u201d He\nlisted as possible causes a big in\ncrease in Federal spending, big\nwage increases or a serious crop\nfailure.\nSenator O'Mahoney said the\nfactors mentioned by Dr. Nourse\n\u201cdo exercise inflationary pressure\u201d\nbut added tljat if Congress wants\na peaceful world it must continue\nto spend billions for European\nrecovery.\nTruman Won't Release\nBikini Test Report\n\u2022y th\u00ab Auociat\u00abd Pr*\u00bb\u00bb\nPresident Truman said today he\nhas no intention of releasing the\nreport of the Bikini atom bomb\ntests.\nTold at a news conference that\nthere was a rumor the report\nmight be released, Mr. Truman\nreplied there was no foundation\nfor such a rumor.\na.\nBET IlL MAKE\nYOU LOOK SILLY\nI BET YOU\nWON\u2019T Sg\nrWTTTIiTlTfllUni\nSpeaking of Gambling\n700 Pupils Dismissed for Failing\nTo Pay Non-Resident Tuition\nFuture Fees to Be Collected in Advance;\nDistrict Loss on Group May Total $5,000\nOne hundred non-resident stu\ndents have been dismissed from\nthe District's public schools for\nnon-payment of tuition fees which\nwould total more than $5,000. the\nBoard of Education informed the\nCommissioners today.\nTo avoid this situation in the\nfuture, the Commissioners told\nschool officials to collect tuition\nfees in advance.\nThe 100 dismissed pupils, who\nlive in nearby Maryland and Vir\nginia, were dropped at the end\nof the first semester, Adelbert W.\nHeinmiller, business admlnistra\nWoods Orders Survey\nOf Landlords' Incomes\nTo Fix Rent Boosts\nCeilings Will Be Lifted\nIn TOO of 600 Areas\nWithin Next Week\nTRUMAN MAY SIGN D. C. Rent\nCurb Today. Page A-3.\nHousing Expediter Tighe Woods\ntoday ordered a survey of landlord\nincomes to determine what rent\nincreases are to be granted under\nthe new control law signed by\nPresident Truman late yesterday.\nAnnouncing the order in a state\nment, Mr. Woods declared the 15\nmonth extension is a \u201cconsiderable\nstrengthening\" of the previous law\nand does not mean \u201ca general rent\nincrease for all tenants.\u201d\nThe new law does require that\nrent ceilings allow landlords a\n\u201cfair operating income.\u201d The sur\nvey is to obtain information for\ncarrying out that part of the law.\nShortly after Mr. Woods an\nnounced his plans. Mr. Truman\ntook another crack at what he\ncalled the real estate lobby.\nThe rent ceiling bill he signed\nyesterday must be a good one, the\nPresident told his news conference,\nin view of the criticism of it in a\ntelegram he has received.\nUnder questioning, Mr. Truman\nsaid the telegram came from the\nNational Association of Real Estate\nBoards. He wasn't releasing the\ntelegram himself, he said, but the\nsender, a Mr. Nelson, was at lib\nerty to do so.\nTrace of Sarcasm.\nThe exchange started with this\nquestion:\n\u201cMr. President, would you care\nto comment on the reactions of\nthe real estate lobby to the rent\ncontrol law?\u201d\nMr. Truman replied, with a trace\nof sarcasm in his voice, that he\nhad a long-winded telegram from\nthe real estate lobby giving him all\nsorts of what-for for signing the\nbill. So, he added, it must be a\ngood bill for that very reason.\nHerbert U. Nelson, executive\nvice president of the realty asso\n1 ciation, was not immediately avail\nable for comment. On Monday,\nhowever, he sent the President a\nwire urging him to consult with\nthe real estate and housing irfOus\ntries before signing any rent bill.\nWord is spreading through the\nindustry that it is time to stop\n(See RENT, Page A-5.)\nW. A. Julian Cut Out\nOf His Wife's Estate\nSy th\u00bb Auociatod Prus\nCINCINNATI. Mar. 31.\u2014United\nStates Treasurer William A. Julian\nwas \u201cby design and intent\u201d cut\nout of his late wife\u2019s $10,000 estate.\nMrs. Gertrude M. Julian\u2019s will\nstipulated that her secretary,\nGeorge A. Argus, and the Provi\ndent Savings Bank Trust Co.,\nshare equally in the estate.\nIn the will, filed yesterday in\nProbate Court, Mrs. Julian said\nthe absence of bequests to others\n\u201cis not by inadvertent omission,\nbut rather by design and intent,\nfor reasons deemed by me to be\nadequate and proper.\u201d\nMrs. Julian died last week..\ntion assistant to the school super- j\nintendent, said. Advance payments j\nwould prevent this from happen\ning again, he added.\nThe Board of Education, School\nSupt. Hobart M. Corning and Mr.]\nHeinmiller called on the Commis\nsioners today to ask that the bill\ning procedure for tuition fees be\nchanged to avoid repetition of this\nsituation. He said some $269,000\nhad been collected in fees so far\nfrom 2,000 nonresident students\nand that the $5,000 apparently\nwas uncollectable. However, the\n(See TUITION, Page A-4.)\nTruman Aim to Bypass\nCongress on Repairing\nWhite House Denied\nOfficial Tells Why Funds\nWere Asked Before Seeking\nAuthorization of Job\nPresident Truman had \u201cno in\ntention whatsoever of bypassing\u201d\nlegislative committees of Congress\non the White House renovation\nproject, Assistant Budget Director\nLeo C. Martin said today, but a\n\u201cmisunderstanding\u201d apparently\ndeveloped.\nMr. Martin was trying to ex\nplain to the House Public Works\nCommittee why a supplementary\n$5,400,000 budget estimate for the\nwork was sent to the Capitol with\nout any previous request for spe\ncific authorization of the job.\nThe question was raised yester\nday by Representatives Pickett,\nDemocrat, of Texas, and Angell,\nRepublican, of Oregon, in a hear\ning before the committee on legis\nlation to establish a commission\nto supervise the renovation.\nPrecedents Mentioned.\nMr. Martin said today he had\nchecked into the matter and\nfound the procedure was based\non precedent. He said a $475,000\nappropriation for White House\nrepairs was voted in 1902, and\none of $375,000 was approved in\n1926.\n\u201cIn neither of these instances\nwas any question raised, either\nin committee or on the floor, as\nto the propriety of making the\nappropriation without specific\nenabling legislation,\u201d Mr. Martin\nsaid today.\nMr. Angell commented these\nitems were handled before adop\ntion of the present rules of the\nHouse.\nMr. Martin said he had been\nin touch with the executive offices\nsince yesterday, and had been\ntold Mr. Truman thought he had\nmade clear his intention to seek\nthe money when he invited Sen\nate and House Public Works Sub\ncommittee members to the White\nHouse to discuss the project.\nHarry G. Hunter, acting com\n(See WHITE HOUSE, Page A-3~)\nClear, Mild Week End\nForecast for Festival;\nBlooms Resist Rain\nHotels Booked Solid\nIn Advance of Crowds\nFor Tidal Basin Show\nThe Tidal Basin wore its loveli\nest dress today, with the cherry\nblossoms resisting the rain and\nready to appear all the brighter\nin expected clear and mild weather\nfor Washington's festival week\nend.\nThe Greater National Capital\nCommittee of the Board of Trade\nsaid the week-end crowds are\nlikely to be the largest in festival\nhistory.\nJust enough petals were flutter\ning to the ground today to provide\nflowery patterns along the walks\nand on the water. National Capital\nParks officials said this is no rea\nson for the thousands of visitors\nto fear that the trees will lose any\nof their beauty during the three\nday celebration.\nPromising fair and mild weather\nfor practically all of the three\nday festival period, the Weather\nBureau forecast clearing skies for\ntomorrow, after showers through\nout today and tonight. Signs\npoint to fair weather Saturday\nand Sunday, although tempera\ntures will be considerably below\nyesterday's near-record of 80 de\ngrees, the forecaster said.\nYesterday\u2019s sunshine almost set\na temperature record for March\n30. The 80-degree reading at 2:30\np.m. was the second highest on\nrecord here for that date, being\ntopped only by the 86-degree\nmaximum of March 30, 1910.\nParks employes yesterday com\npleted the job of spraying the\nnearly 600 cherry trees with a\nspecial hormone solution. They\nfinished with the conventional\nsprayer, after experimenting with\na turbine fan. known as a mist\nblower, and finding it less effec\ntive.\nCapt. Mark Raspberry of the\npark police noted an increase in\nyesterday's crowds over Tuesday\u2019s\nestimated 25,000 blossom visitors,\nTcontinued on Page A-4, Col. 1.)\nChinese Bandits Beat 15\nFrench Catholic Sisters\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nCANTON, Mar. 31. \u2014Fifteen\nFrench Catholic sisters serving in\na leprosarium at Shihlung, 37\nmiles east of Canton, were beaten\nby 30 bandits last Sunday, it was\ndisclosed today.\nSister St. Lazare was badly\nwounded and Sister Marie-Cen\nacle, head of the hospital, was\ninjured severely.\nThe bandits took 20,000 Hong\nKong dollars ($5,000 United\nStates! from the hospital.\nFrench Consul Paul Viaud said\nhe has asked Canton pacification\nheadquarters for the arrest of the\nbandits and protection for the\nCatholic sisters. He said it was\nhis second request for their pro\ntection.\nMilk Showing Any Trace of DDT\nBanned in Interstate Shipment\nBy James Birchfield\nDDT. slow death for most insect\npests, may be detected in milk\nfrom herds where the insecticide\nis used as a fly-control agent in\ndairy barns.\nAnnouncing that traces of the\ninsecticide have been found in\nmilk after the use of DDT as a\nbarn spray, the Food and Drug\nAdministration has banned inter\nstate shipments of milk containing\neven the smallest particle of the\nchemical.\nDairy farmers also are being\nwarned by Agrieulture Depart\nment entomologists against the\ncontinued use of DDT as a barn\nspray and as an insect control\nagent on dairy animals.\nCommissioner P. B. Dunbar of\nthe Food and Drug Administra\ntion said the ruling against DDT\ncontaminated milk was made after\nlengthy studies definitely proved\nthat the chemical appears in milk\nafter its use in barns and on\ncattle.\nHe explained the ruling is\nbased on a law which prohibits\nthe presence of an added poison\nin food. No tolerance for DDT\nin milk will be allowed, he said.\nFood and Drug Administration\ntoxicologists explained that no\nproven cases are on record where\nDDT contained in food has caused\npoisoning.\nThey added, however, that tests\nwhere rather large amounts of\nthe chemical have been fed\nmother rats have resulted in defl\n(See DDT, Page A-6.)\nRowell Beaten\nBy Policemen,\nRelative Says\nBrother-in-Law Gives\nNames; Threatened\nOn Jury Testimony\nThe mysterious beating of Cab\nDriver James Rowell on January\n14 today was laid at the door of\ntwo police plainclothesmen by Mr.\nRowell's brother-in-law.\nDonnia De Griffion, brother of\nMr. Rowell\u2019s wife, told reporters\nMr. Rowell gave him the names of\nthe two men about five hours after\nthe beating. He gave the press\nthe names after appearing before\na grand jury investigating the\nRowell case.\nMr. Rowell, who was recalled by\nthe grand jury today, has stead\nfastly contended he did not know\nwho beat him up in the early\nmorning hours of January 14 at\nThomas Circle.\nAfter his grand jury appear\nance, Mr. De Griffion also told re\nporters he was threatened twice\nyesterday and one caller warned\nhim \u201cyour body will be found\nfloating down the river\u201d if he tes\ntified.\nNo Action Against Policemen.\nMystery was cast over the beat\ning by Mr. Rowell's insistence that\nhe did not know the identity of\nhis assailants. When a number\nof men paraded before him in a\nline-up he said be could not rec\nognize any of them as his assail\nants.\nAmong those in the line-up\nwere Sergt. James Roche and Pvt.\nAngelo Bonaccorsy. Police Supt.\nRobert J. Barrett announced\nshortly after the beating that he\nhad transferred Sergt. Roche and\nPvt. Bonaccarsy because of re\nports they were connected with\nthe beating.\nA police investigation, however,\nfailed to result in any action\nagainst the two policemen. Maj.\nBarrett referred the case to\nUnited States Attorney George\nMorris Fay. Subsequently, the\nJustice Department went into it\nas a possible civil rights violation.\nUniformed Police Interrupt.\nMr. De Griffion said Mr. Rowell\ntold him the circumstances of\nthe beating and who had done it\nwhile the cab driver was being\ntreated at Prince Georges County\nHospital at about 10 a.m. on Jan\nuary 14.\nMr. Rowell. Mr. De Griffion\nsaid, told him that while he was\nj being beaten up, two uniformed\ni policemen reached the scene and\nasked, \u201cWhat's going on here?\u201d\ni At that point, according to Mr.\nDe Griffion's story, the two as\nsailants identified themselves as\nplainclothesmen, gave their names\nand showed their credentials.\nTwo Threatening Calls.\nTwo uniformed policemen. Pvt.\nM. W. McClanahan and Pvt. D.\nF. Reid of the second precinct,\nreported to their superior officers\nthey reached the beating sfifene in\nresponse to calls for help, but saw\ni nothing when they arrived.\nMr. De Griffion had been sub\npoenaed to appear before the grand\n1 jury investigating the Rowell case\nTuesday but was not reached.\nYesterday morning, he told re\nporters, he got a telephone call\nabout 7 a.m. by a man who said:\n\u201cWe know you didn't testify yes\nterday. It would pay you not to\ntestify because if you do. your\nbody will be found floating down\nthe river.\u201d\nHe said he received another\nthreatening call about 3 p.m. yes\njterday from a man with a differ\n(See ROWELL, Page A-3.)\nGov. Tuck Acts to Bar\nVepco Strike May 6\nBy the Associated Press\nRICHMOND. Va.. Mar. 31\u2014Gov.\nTuck issued a proclamation today\nstating that the Commonwealth\nof Virginia will seize plants and\nequipment of the Virginia Electric\nPower Co. at 12:01 a.m. May 6\nto prevent interruption of services\nby a strike.\nIn an executive order issued at\nthe same time under the State\u2019s\nPublic Utilities Labor Relations\ni Act. the Governor designated the\n1 three members of the State Cor\nporation Commission as his agent\nto operate VEPCO plants and\ni equipment should it become nec\ni essary.\nThe Governor acted within a\nfew minutes after he received a\ntelegram from H. M. Ware, System\nCouncil chairman of the Inter\nnational Brotherhood of Electrical\nWorkers\u2019 local unions, notifying\nhim that the union was giving no\ntice of intention to strike at mid\nnight May 5.\nIt's Fitting-Out Time\nOn the Water Front\nIt\u2019s fitting-out time again on\nWashington\u2019s water front as\nboatmen prepare for a busy\nseason afloat. Starting tomor\nrow, The Star will run a weekly\npage on the latest in boating\nand fishing news here and on\nChesapeake Bay.\nWatch for the first spring\nboat page in tomorrow\u2019s sport\nsection of\nStye Star","height":"32188","width":"22656"}}
